==\n*[http://www.nber.org/people/james_hines James R. Hines Jr.], PROFILE: National Bureau of Economic Research\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?reload=9&v=mZm2xkgocC8 Territorial is the right option], James Hines speaking at the [[American Enterprise Institute]], September 2012\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hines Jr., James R.}}\n[[Category:University of Michigan faculty]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century American economists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American economists]]\n[[Category:Corporate tax avoidance]]\n[[Category:International taxation]]\n[[Category:Tax evasion]]\n[[Category:Tax avoidance]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American tax economist}}\n\n{{Infobox economist\n| name             = James R. Hines Jr.\n| school_tradition = <!--Should be selected from the list of 'schools of economic thought'-->\n| image            =\n| caption          =  James R. Hines Jr. testifying to the Senate Finance Committee (26 April 2016)\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1958|7|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Chicago]], U.S.\n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| nationality      = American\n| institutions     = [[University of Michigan]]<br />[[Harvard University]]\n| field            = [[Public economics]]\n| alma_mater       = [[Yale University]] (BSc, MSc)<br />[[Harvard University]] (PhD)\n| doctoral_advisor = [[Lawrence Summers]] \n| doctoral_students = \n| influences       =  \n| influenced       =\n| contributions    = {{hlist|[[Corporate tax]]|[[Tax havens]]|[[Corporate tax havens]]|[[Base erosion and profit shifting]]}}\n| awards           = Daniel M. Holland Medal, [[National Tax Association]] (2017)\n| signature        = \n| repec_prefix     = e \n| repec_id         = phi111\n| website          = {{url|1=https://lsa.umich.edu/econ/people/faculty/jrhines.html|2=James R. Hines Jr.}}\n}}\n\n{{taxation}}\n\n'''James R. Hines Jr.''' (born 9 July 1958) is an American [[economist]] and a founder of academic research into corporate-focused [[tax havens]], and the effect of U.S. corporate tax policy on the behaviors of U.S. multinationals.  His papers were some of the first to analyse ''[[base erosion and profit shifting|profit shifting]]'', and to establish quantitative features of tax havens. Hines showed that being a tax haven could be a prosperous strategy for a jurisdiction, and controversially, that tax havens can promote economic growth.  Hines showed that use of tax havens by U.S. multinationals had maximized long-term U.S. exchequer tax receipts, at the expense of other jurisdictions. Hines is the most cited author on the research of tax havens, and his work on tax havens was relied upon by the [[Council of Economic Advisors|CEA]] when drafting the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].\n\n==Biography==\nJames Hines was born in Chicago in 1958.  He went to [[Yale University]] for his B.Sc and M.Sc in 1980.  He completed his PhD in [[Harvard University]] in 1986.  After various teaching and research posts in [[Princeton University]] and Harvard University, in 1997 he became Professor of Economics at the [[University of Michigan]].  Hines is a research associate of the [[National Bureau of Economic Research]], and a research director of the International Tax Policy Forum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ideas.repec.org/e/phi111.html|title=RePec DATABASE: James R. Hines Jr.|publisher=St. Louis Federal Reserve}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://lsa.umich.edu/econ/people/faculty/jrhines/_jcr_content/file.res/James%20Hines%20cv%20May%202018.pdf|title=James R. Hines Jr.|date=May 2018|publisher=[[University of Michigan]]}}</ref>\n\nHines is the most cited author on research into [[tax havens]], and has co-authored several papers in the {{slink|#Most important papers on tax havens}}, including the most cited paper.<ref name=\"respec\"/>  Hines has testified to Congress on public tax policy on a number of occasions,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/person/?jameshines|title=James R. Hines Jr.|publisher=C-SPAN}}</ref> and is quoted on related issues by the financial media, such as the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]] (\"TCJA\").<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/you-say-fiddy-i-say-foedeeno-one-knows-what-to-call-new-tax-provisions-1523545935|title=Taxes Are Hard\u2014So Is Pronouncing New Tax Law Acronyms Like FDII|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=12 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/lost-in-the-tax-debate-would-growth-benefit-1507747815|title=Lost in the Tax Debate: Would Growth Benefit?|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=11 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/81f819be-b21c-11e7-a398-73d59db9e399|title=White House says lower corporate tax will lift wages|newspaper=[[The Financial Times]]|date=16 October 2017|quote=\u201cAre these fanciful numbers? It is a mistake to dismiss them because everyone agrees the mechanism sounds right,\u201d said&nbsp;James Hines, a professor at University of Michigan Law School, whose work is cited by the CEA.}}</ref>\n\n==Tax haven research==\n===Hines-Rice paper===\nIn February 1994, Hines and his Harvard PhD student, Eric M. Rice, published their 1990 [[National Bureau of Economic Research]] (\"NBER\") working paper (No. 3477), in the ''[[Quarterly Journal of Economics]]'', on the use of tax havens by U.S. multinationals, which contained a number of important findings.<ref name=\"h3\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.nber.org/papers/w3477.pdf|title=Fiscal Paradise: Foreign Tax Havens and American Business |author1=James R. Hines Jr.|author2=Eric M. Rice|quote=We identify 41 countries and regions as tax havens for the purposes of U. S. businesses. Together the seven tax havens with populations greater than one million (Hong Kong, Ireland, Liberia, Lebanon, Panama, Singapore, and Switzerland) account for 80 percent of total tax haven population and 89 percent of tax haven GDP. |journal=Quarterly Journal of Economics (Harvard/MIT)|date=February 1994|volume=9|issue=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/special-report/2000/01/27/gimme-shelter|title=Gimme shelter - A survey of globalisation and tax|newspaper=[[The Economist]]|date=27 January 2000}}</ref>\n\n{{ordered list|[[Base erosion and profit shifting]] (\"BEPS\"). Hines-Rice showed U.S. multinationals were using non-traditional tax havens, like Ireland and Singapore, that had large networks of [[tax treaties]] (which traditional tax havens are restricted from having), enabling them to avoid corporate taxes in all jurisdictions that had [[tax treaties]] with the haven, by a technique they called ''profit shifting'';<ref name=\"be\">{{cite web|url=https://chicagounbound.uchicago.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2385&context=law_and_economics|title=What Do We Know About Base Erosion and Profit Shifting? A Review of the Empirical Literature|publisher=[[University of Chicago]]|author=Dhammika Dharmapala|date=2014|quote= It focuses particularly on the dominant approach within the economics literature on income shifting, which dates back to Hines and Rice (1994) and which we refer to as the \u201cHines-Rice\u201d approach.|page=1|author-link=Dhammika Dharmapala}}</ref>\n\n|[[Corporate tax havens]]. Hines-Rice noted that several of the most favoured locations for U.S. multinationals, such as Ireland, had normal ''headline'' corporate tax rates, but their tax regimes enabled accounting techniques to produce much lower ''effective'' corporate tax rates (e.g. Ireland was the lowest at 4%); these were the little-understood [[BEPS]] tools of the emerging [[corporate tax havens]];<ref name=\"cesifo\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.cesifo-group.de/DocDL/cesifo1_wp7171.pdf|title=Firms, Trade and Profit Shifting: Evidence from Aggregate Data|author1=S\u00e9bastien Laffitte|author2=Farid Toubal|journal=[[CESifo Economic Studies]]|date=July 2018|quote=Concerning the characterization of tax havens, we follow the definition proposed by Hines and Rice (1994) which has been recently used by Dharmapala and Hines (2009). A tax haven is defined as a location with low corporate tax rates, banking and business secrecy, advance communication facilities and self-promotion as an offshore financial centre (Hines and Rice, 1994, Appendix 1 p. 175)|page=8}}</ref><ref name=\"tf\">{{cite web|url=https://taxfoundation.org/economics-international-taxation/|title=EDITORIAL: The Economics of International Taxation|publisher=[[Tax Foundation]]|date=22 January 2002}}</ref>\n\n|[[Tax haven#Definitions|Definition of a tax haven]]. Hines-Rice felt the variations between havens was too material for a single definition, beyond a requirement for ''low effective tax rates''; distortions from ''profit shifting'' led them to note proxies, including: the [[Corporate haven#GDP-per-capita tax haven proxy|GDP-per-capita proxy]], and the [[Corporate haven#Proxy tests|corporate profitabity proxy]];<ref name=\"cesifo\"/> in June 2018, these tools were used to show that Ireland was the largest tax haven;<ref name=\"z1\">{{cite web|url=http://gabriel-zucman.eu/files/TWZ2018.pdf|title=The Missing Profits of Nations|author1=Gabriel Zucman|publisher=[[National Bureau of Economic Research]]|author2=Thomas T\u00f8rsl\u00f8v|author3=Ludvig Wier|date=8 June 2018|author1-link=Gabriel Zucman}}</ref><ref name=\"z2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/corporations-push-profits-into-tax-havens-as-countries-struggle-in-pursuit-study-says-1528634659|title=Zucman:Corporations Push Profits Into Corporate Tax Havens as Countries Struggle in Pursuit, Gabrial Zucman Study Says|quote=Such profit shifting leads to a total annual revenue loss of $200 billion globally|newspaper=[[Wall Street Journal]]|date=10 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"z3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/economy/ireland-is-the-world-s-biggest-corporate-tax-haven-say-academics-1.3528401?mode=sample&auth-failed=1&pw-origin=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.irishtimes.com%2Fbusiness%2Feconomy%2Fireland-is-the-world-s-biggest-corporate-tax-haven-say-academics-1.3528401|title=Ireland is the world's biggest corporate 'tax haven', say academics|quote=New Gabriel Zucman study claims State shelters more multinational profits than the entire Caribbean|newspaper=[[Irish Times]]|date=13 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n|[[Corporate haven#U.S. as BEPS winner|U.S. as a beneficiary from tax havens]].  An unexpected conclusion from Hines-Rice was that: ''low foreign tax rates [from tax havens] ultimately enhance U.S. tax collections''; by paying little/no foreign taxes, U.S. multinationals had avoided building up foreign tax credits; the 15.5% [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]] levy would prove this [[Base erosion and profit shifting#Complex agendas|finding again]] in 2017.<ref name=\"dryng\">{{cite journal|title=Using Financial Accounting Data to Examine the Effect of Foreign Operations Located in Tax Havens and Other Countries on US Multinational Firms' Tax Rates|author1=Scott Dyreng|author2=Bradley P. Lindsey|date=12 October 2009|quote=Finally, we find that US firms with operations in some tax haven countries have higher federal tax rates on foreign income than other firms. This result suggests that in some cases, tax haven operations may increase US tax collections at the expense of foreign country tax collections.|journal=[[Journal of Accounting Research]]|volume = 47|issue=5|pages=1283\u20131316|doi=10.1111/j.1475-679X.2009.00346.x}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d8b8cb98-c956-11de-b551-00144feabdc0|title=Tax havens benefits spelt out|newspaper=[[The Financial Times]]|date=4 November 2009|quote=The [Hines] study said \u201ca large body of economic research over the last 15 years\u201d contradicted the popular view that offshore centres erode tax collections, divert economic activity and otherwise burden nearby high-tax countries.}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\nThe 1994 Hines-Rice paper is recognised as the first important paper into [[BEPS]] and tax havens,<ref name=\"be\"/><ref name=\"eup\">{{cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/sites/info/files/dp_055_en.pdf|title=Banks in Tax Havens: First Evidence based on Country-by-Country Reporting|page=50|author1=Vincent Bouvatier|author2=Gunther Capelle-Blancard |author3=Anne-Laure Delatte| quote=Figure D: Tax Haven Literature Review: A Typology|publisher=[[EU Commission]]|date=July 2017}}</ref> and it is the most cited research paper in history on tax havens.<ref name=\"respec\">{{cite web|url=https://ideas.repec.org/cgi-bin/htsearch?form=extended&wm=wrd&dt=range&ul=&q=tax+haven&cmd=Search%21&wf=4BFF&s=C&db=&de=|title=RePEc Database of Economic Papers |publisher=Federal Reserve of St. Louis|quote=Tax Havens by Most Cited}}</ref> The 1994 Hines-Rice paper has been cited by all subsequent most cited research papers into tax havens, including by [[Mihir A. Desai|Desai]],<ref name=\"demand\">{{cite journal|title=The Demand for Tax Haven Operations|author1=Mihir A.Desai|author2=C Fritz Foley|author3=James R. Hines Jr|journal=[[Journal of Public Economics]]|volume=9|issue=3|pages=513\u2013531|doi=10.1016/j.jpubeco.2005.04.004|year=2006}}</ref> [[Dhammika Dharmapala|Dharmapala]],<ref name=\"d1\">{{cite journal|author1=Dhammika Dharmapala|author2=James R. Hines Jr.|pages=1058\u20131068|volume=93 |issue=9\u201310| url=http://faculty.smu.edu/millimet/classes/eco6375/papers/dharmapala%20hines.pdf|title=Which countries become tax havens?|journal=[[Journal of Public Economics]]|date=2009|doi=10.1016/j.jpubeco.2009.07.005|author1-link=Dhammika Dharmapala}}</ref> [[Joel Slemrod|Slemrod]],<ref name=\"slemrod\">{{cite journal|url=http://gabriel-zucman.eu/files/teaching/SlemrodWilson09.pdf|title=Tax competition with parasitic tax havens|date=6 September 2009|journal=[[Journal of Public Economics]]|author1=Joel Slemrod|author2=John D. Wilson|author1-link=Joel Slemrod}}</ref> and [[Gabriel Zucman|Zucman]].<ref name=\"z1\"/><ref name=\"zucmiss\">{{cite journal|url=http://qje.oxfordjournals.org/content/128/3/1321|title=The Missing Wealth of Nations: Are Europe and the U.S. net Debtors or net Creditors?|journal=The Quarterly Journal of Economics|volume=128|issue=3|pages=1321\u20131364|date=August 2013|author=Gabriel Zucman|doi=10.1093/qje/qjt012|citeseerx=10.1.1.371.3828|author-link=Gabriel Zucman}}</ref>\n\nThe two most recent U.S. congressional investigations into tax havens: the 2008 investigation by the [[Government Accountability Office]],<ref name=\"congress1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gao.gov/assets/290/284522.pdf|title=INTERNATIONAL TAXATION: Large U.S. Corporations and Federal Contractors with Subsidiaries in Jurisdictions Listed as Tax Havens or Financial Privacy Jurisdictions|publisher=[[Government Accountability Office]]|quote=Table 1: Jurisdictions Listed as Tax Havens or Financial Privacy Jurisdictions and the Sources of Those Jurisdictions | page=12 | date=18 December 2008}}</ref> and the 2015 investigation by the [[Congressional Research Service]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://digitalcommons.ilr.cornell.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2387&context=key_workplace|title=Tax Havens: International Tax Avoidance and Evasion |author=Jane Gravelle|publisher=Cornell University | page=4 |quote=Table 1. Countries Listed on Various Tax Haven Lists | date=15 January 2015}}</ref> identify the 1994 Hines-Rice paper as the first credible list of global tax havens, and the first quantitative analysis of what constitutes a tax haven.\n\n===Subsequent research===\nHis subsequent 2007\u20132011 papers on tax havens showed that major tax havens, including Ireland, Singapore, Bermuda, Luxembourg, Hong Kong, were well governed and prosperous economies,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2013/03/28/175550945/what-makes-a-good-tax-haven|publisher=[[National Public Radio]]|date=28 March 2013|title=Interview with James R. Hines Jr.: What makes a good tax haven}}</ref> from being tax havens: ''Tax havens are successful players in the world economy''.<ref name=\"h1\">{{cite journal|url=https://repository.law.umich.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=https://www.google.ie/&httpsredir=1&article=1716&context=articles|title=Treasure Islands|pages=103\u2013125|author=James R. Hines Jr.|quote=Table 1: 52 Tax Havens|journal=[[Journal of Economic Perspectives]]|volume=4|issue=24|date=2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/bitstream/handle/2027.42/39181/921.pdf?sequence=1|title=Do Tax Havens Flourish|author=James R. Hines Jr.|journal=National Bureau of Economic Research, Tax Policy and the Economy|quote=ABSTRACT: Per capita real GDP in tax haven countries grew at an average annual rate of 3.3 percent between 1982 and 1999, which compares favorably to the world average of 1.4 percent.|volume=19|pages=65\u201399|date=2005|doi=10.1086/tpe.19.20061896}}</ref>  He also asserted that tax havens could ''stimulate economic activity in nearby high-tax countries'', by addressing issues in their tax systems,<ref name=\"h2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bus.umich.edu/otpr/WP2007-3.pdf|title=Tax Havens|quote=There are roughly 45 major tax havens in the world today. Examples include Andorra, Ireland, Luxembourg and Monaco in Europe, Hong Kong and Singapore in Asia, and the Cayman Islands, the Netherlands Antilles, and Panama in the Americas. |author=James R. Hines Jr.|publisher=[[The New Palgrave Dictionary of Economics]]|date=2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://economix.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/04/04/tax-havens-and-treasure-hunts/|title=Tax havens and treasure hunts|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|quote=Some economists champion tax havens. In an article in the Journal of Economic Perspectives published last fall (also titled \"Treasure Islands\"), James R. Hines Jr. of the University of Michigan argued that they contribute to financial market competition, encourage investment in high-tax countries and promote economic growth.  Like many economists, Professor Hines expresses far more confidence in the market than in the state. He worries more about possible overtaxation than about undertaxation of corporate income. He does not enage with such concepts as \u201ctax justice.\u201d|date=11 April 2011}}</ref> however this conclusion has been controversial and has drawn criticism from advocates of ''tax justice'' as being supportive of corporate tax avoidance by multinationals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://taxjustice.blogspot.com/2010/03/jim-hines-fails-to-defend-secrecy.html|title=Jim Hines fails to defend secrecy jurisdictions|publisher=[[Tax Justice Network]]|date=3 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://treasureislands.org/the-arguments/|title=Tax havens' arguments in their defence \u2013 and why they are wrong |quote=First, many these claims rest heavily on work done by James Hines of the University of Michigan and a few others \u2013 research that is fatally flawed. |author=Nicholas Shaxson|date=19 November 2010|author-link=Nicholas Shaxson }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/five-myths-about-tax-havens/2016/04/15/76d001d2-0255-11e6-b823-707c79ce3504_story.html?noredirect=on|title=Five myths about tax havens|quote=According to economics professor James Hines, tax havens serve as healthy competition for high-tax countries, nudging them toward less-restrictive financial policy. By providing alternatives to tightly controlled financial sectors, Hines wrote in a 2010 paper, tax havens discourage regulations that act as \u201ca drag on local economies.\u201d|newspaper=The Washington Post|author=Nicholas Shaxson|date=15 April 2016|author-link=Nicholas Shaxson}}</ref>\n\nWhile Hines always avoided constructing overly specific or quantitative definitions of a tax haven, because of the variability in the types of economies that he had identified as  tax havens, Hines does use a general definition that he employed during research with fellow tax-haven expert, Dhammaka Dharmapala, in 2009:<ref name=\"d1\"/>\n\n{{quote|Tax havens are typically small, well-governed states that impose low or zero tax rates on foreign investors.|title=\"Multinational Firms and Tax Havens\"|source=[[The Review of Economics and Statistics]] (2016)<ref>{{cite journal| url =https://repository.law.umich.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2831&context=articles|title=Multinational Firms and Tax Havens|author1=James R. Hines Jr.|author2=Anna Gumpert|author3=Monika Schnitzer|date=2016|journal=[[The Review of Economics and Statistics]]|pages=713\u2013727|volume=98|issue=4}}</ref>}}\n\nIn November 2017, Hines was awarded the  Daniel M. Holland Medal by the [[National Tax Association]] for his work,<ref name=\"NTA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ntanet.org/awards/2017/12/james-r-hines-jr-2017-holland-award-recipient/|title=James R. Hines Jr., 2017 Holland Award Recipient|publisher=[[National Tax Association]]|date=December 2017}}</ref> the second youngest winner in the medal's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2017/11/jim-hines-receives-2017-holland-medal.html|title=Jim Hines receives Holland Medal|publisher=TaxProf|date=10 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, his papers were cited by Harvard Professor [[Mihir A. Desai]] as ones that: ''changed the field and provided the roadmap for much of the next thirty years''.<ref name=\"NTA\"/>\n\n==Multinational tax research==\nAs well as his work on [[BEPS]] and on tax havens, Hines is known for research into how U.S. corporate taxation, and the marginal rate of U.S. corporation tax, drives the behaviours of U.S multinationals.  Hines has been a strong advocate of moving the U.S. to a \"territorial\" tax model.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/09/14/territorial-taxation-offshore-corporations-congress_n_961922.html?guccounter=1|title=Corporations Pressure Congress, White House Over 'Territorial Taxation' Of Offshore Profits|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=14 September 2011|quote=\u201cWe are so out of step with the rest of the world right now. It is important for us to adopt a territorial system,\u201d said University of Michigan Law School Professor James Hines.}}</ref>  In 2016, Hines, working with German academics, showed that German multinationals make little use of tax havens because the German corporate taxation system follows a \"territorial\" model.<ref name=\"hines2016\">{{cite journal| url = https://repository.law.umich.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2831&context=articles|title=Multinational Firms and Tax Havens|author1=James R. Hines Jr.|author2=Anna Gumpert|author3=Monika Schnitzer|date=2016|journal=[[The Review of Economics and Statistics]]|page=714|quote=Germany taxes only 5% of the active foreign business profits of its resident corporations. [..] Furthermore, German firms do not have incentives to structure their foreign operations in ways that avoid repatriating income. Therefore, the tax incentives for German firms to establish tax haven affiliates are likely to differ from those of U.S. firms and bear strong similarities to those of other G-7 and OECD firms.|volume=98|issue=4}}</ref>  Hines cites the experience of Ireland, a feature on all of Hines' tax haven lists, who has [[Ireland as a tax haven#Global \"knowledge hub\" for \"selling into Europe\"|rarely attracted firms from \"territorial\" taxation systems]].\n\nHis research in this area was cited, although sometimes controversially so, by the [[Council of Economic Advisors]] (\"CEA\") in drafting the TCJA legislation in 2017;<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/17/us/politics/white-house-push-to-help-workers-through-corporate-tax-cut-draws-skepticism.html|title=White House Push to Help Workers Through Corporate Tax Cut Draws Skepticism|newspaper=New York Times|date=17 October 2017|quote=But the CEA did not misinterpret the Desai, Foley, and Hines paper.}}</ref> and advocating for reducing U.S. corporate taxes and moving to a hybrid \"territorial\" tax system framework, in order to drive U.S employment and wage growth.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/sites/whitehouse.gov/files/documents/Tax%20Reform%20and%20Wages.pdf|publisher=[[Council of Economic Advisors]]|title=TAX CUTS AND JOBS ACT OF 2017 Corporate Tax Reform and Wages: Theory and Evidence|quote=Applying Hines and Rice\u2019s (1994) findings to a statutory corporate rate reduction of 15 percentage points (from 35 to 20 percent) suggests that reduced profit shifting would result in more than $140 billion of repatriated profit based on 2016 numbers.|date=17 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Hines tax havens==\n{{see also|Tax havens#Tax haven lists}}\n\n===Hines-Rice 1994 list===\nBecause it is cited as the first coherent academic list of tax havens, the 41 jurisdictions from Appendix 2 in Hines-Rice (1994) are listed below, in the three sub-categories Hines-Rice used.  The 7 ''major tax havens'' identified by Hines-Rice, who represent over 89% of tax haven GDP, are marked with a dagger (\u2020).<ref name=\"h3\"/>\n\nHines-Rice note that the U.S. IRS had identified 29 of their list as potential tax havens in 1987:\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n*Antigua & Barbuda \n*Bahamas \n*Bahrain \n*Barbados \n*Belize  \n*Bermuda\n*British Virgin Islands \n*Cayman Islands\n*The Channel Islands\n*Cook Islands\n*Cyprus\n*Gibraltar\n*Grenada\n*Hong Kong\u2020\n*Ireland\u2020\n*Isle of Man\n*Liberia\u2020\n*Liechtenstein\n*Luxembourg\n*Montserrat\n*Netherlands Antilles\n*Panama\u2020\n*St. Kitts\n*St. Vincent\n*Singapore\u2020\n*Switzerland\u2020\n*Turks & Caicos\n*U. K. Caribbean Islands\n*Vanuatu\n}}\n\nHines-Rice note that Beauchamp had identified 7 of their list as potential tax havens in 1983:\n*Anguilla \n*Andorra \n*Jordan \n*Lebanon\u2020 \n*Macao\n*Monaco\n*St. Martin\n\nHines-Rice note that Doggart had identified 5 of their list as potential tax havens in 1983:\n*Dominica\n*Maldives\n*Malta\n*Marshall Islands\n*St. Lucia\n\n===Hines 2010 list{{anchor|Hines 2010 list}}===\nIn a 2010 research paper, Hines produced a revised list of 52 tax havens, and also a method of quantifying and ranking the largest of them (Hines did not rank the whole list).<ref name=\"h1\"/>  Only two of the ten largest havens in Hines' 2010 list appeared in the OECD's 2000 list of tax havens (by 2017, the OECD list only contained Trinidad & Tobago).<ref name=\"OECD havens\"/>  A major quantitative study in July 2017 study by the University of Amsterdam's CORPNET group, produced a list of havens that matched nine of the ten largest havens in Hines' list, but split into two types of haven: [[Conduit and Sink OFCs|Conduit and Sinks]].<ref name=\"xx\">{{cite journal |author1=Javier Garcia-Bernardo|author2=Jan Fichtner|author3=Frank W. Takes|author4=Eelke M. Heemskerk | url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-017-06322-9 | volume=7 | issue=6246 | title=Uncovering Offshore Financial Centers: Conduits and Sinks in the Global Corporate Ownership Network | journal=Scientific Reports | date=24 July 2017}}</ref>  Another major quantitative study in June 2018 by [[Gabriel Zucman]] (et alia), produced a list whose ten largest havens also matched nine of Hines' top ten havens from 2010.<ref name=\"z1\"/>  Zucman calculated that Ireland had now become the largest of the ten major havens (Ireland's largest firms, Apple, Google and Facebook were smaller in 2010).<ref name=\"zux\">{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/economy/ireland-is-the-world-s-biggest-corporate-tax-haven-say-academics-1.3528401?mode=sample&auth-failed=1&pw-origin=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.irishtimes.com%2Fbusiness%2Feconomy%2Fireland-is-the-world-s-biggest-corporate-tax-haven-say-academics-1.3528401|title=Ireland is the world's biggest corporate 'tax haven', say academics|quote=New Gabriel Zucman study claims State shelters more multinational profits than the entire Caribbean|newspaper=Irish Times|date=13 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nTen largest havens, as specifically estimated by Hines, from the Hines 2010 list of 52 tax havens:<ref name=\"h1\"/>\n\n{{ordered list|Luxembourg*\u2021 \n|Cayman Islands*\u2021  \n|Ireland*\u2020  \n|Switzerland*\u2020   \n|Bermuda*\u2021  \n|Hong Kong*\u2021 \n|Jersey\u2021\u0394  \n|Netherlands*\u2020  \n|Singapore*\u2020   \n|British Virgin Islands*\u2021\u0394\n}}\n\n(*) Identified as one of the largest 10 corporate tax havens on the [[Gabriel Zucman#Zucman-T\u00f8rsl\u00f8v-Wier 2018 list|Zucman-T\u00f8rsl\u00f8v-Wier 2018 list]] in 2018 (Cayman and the British Virgin Islands appear as ''Caribbean'').<ref name=\"z1\"/><br />\n(\u2020) Identified as one of the 5 [[Conduit and Sink OFCs#Conduit OFC|Conduits]] (Ireland, Singapore, Switzerland, the Netherlands, and the United Kingdom), by CORPNET in 2017.<br />\n(\u2021) Identified as one of the largest 5 [[Conduit and Sink OFCs#Sink OFC|Sinks]] (British Virgin Islands, Luxemburg, Hong Kong, Jersey, Bermuda), by CORPNET in 2017.<br />\n(\u0394) Identified on the first, and the largest, OECD 2000 list of 35 tax havens (the OECD list only contained Trinidad & Tobago by 2017).<ref name=\"OECD havens\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oecd.org/ctp/harmful/2090192.pdf|title=Towards Global Tax Co-operation|date=April 2000|page=17|publisher=[[OECD]]|quote=TAX HAVENS: 1.Andorra 2.Anguilla 3.Antigua and Barbuda 4.Aruba 5.Bahamas 6.Bahrain 7.Barbados 8.Belize 9.British Virgin Islands 10.Cook Islands 11.Dominica 12.Gibraltar 13.Grenada 14.Guernsey 15.Isle of Man 16.Jersey 17.Liberia 18.Liechtenstein 19.Maldives 20.Marshall Islands 21.Monaco 22.Montserrat 23.Nauru 24.Net Antilles 25.Niue 26.Panama 27.Samoa 28.Seychelles 29.St. Lucia 30.St. Kitts & Nevis 31.St. Vincent and the Grenadines 32.Tonga 33.Turks & Caicos 34.U.S. Virgin Islands 35.Vanuatu}}</ref>\n\nThe full list of 52 tax havens from the Hines 2010 list, are shown below (Hines did not rank the full list, only the largest):\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n\n{{ordered list\n|Andorra\u0394\n|Anguilla\u2021\u0394\n|Antigua and Barbuda\u0394\n|Aruba\u0394\n|Bahamas\u2021\u0394\n|Bahrain\u2195\u0394\n|Barbados\u2195\u0394\n|Belize\u2021\u0394\n|Bermuda\u2021\n|British Virgin Islands\u2021\u0394\n|Cayman Islands\u2021\n|Cook Islands\u0394\n|Costa Rica\n|Cyprus\u2021\n|Djibouti\n|Dominica\u0394\n|Gibraltar\u2021\u0394\n|Grenada\u2195\u0394\n|Guernsey\u0394\n|Hong Kong\u2021\n|Ireland\u2020\n|Isle of Man\u0394\n|Jersey\u2021\u0394\n|Jordan\n|Lebanon\n|Liberia\u2021\u0394\n|Liechtenstein\u2021\u0394\n|Luxembourg\u2021\n|Macao\u2195\n|Maldives\u0394\n|Malta\u2021\n|Marshall Islands\u2021\u2195\u0394\n|Mauritius\u2021\n|Micronesia\n|Monaco\u2021\u0394\n|Montserrat\u0394\n|Nauru\u2021\u0394\n|Netherlands\u2020 & Antilles\u0394\n|Niue\u0394\n|Panama\u2195\u0394\n|Samoa\u2021\u2195\u0394\n|San Marino\n|Seychelles\u2021\u0394\n|Singapore\u2020\n|St. Kitts and Nevis\u0394\n|St. Lucia\u2195\u0394\n|St. Martin\n|St. Vincent and the Grendines\u2021\u0394\n|Switzerland\u2020\n|Tonga\u0394\n|Turks and Caicos\u0394\n|Vanuatu\u0394\n}}\n}}\n\n(\u2020) Identified as one of the 5 [[Conduit and Sink OFCs#Conduit OFC|Conduits]] by CORPNET in 2017; the above list has 4 of the 5.<br />\n(\u2021) Identified as one of the largest 24 [[Conduit and Sink OFCs#Sink OFC|Sinks]] by CORPNET in 2017; the above list has 21 of the 24.<br />\n(\u2195) Identified on the European Union's first 2017 list of 17 tax havens; the above list contains 8 of the 17.<ref name=\"eu havens\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/c4d721dc-d9cf-11e7-a039-c64b1c09b482|title=EU puts 17 countries on blacklist|newspaper=Financial Times|date=5 December 2017|quote=The 17 countries on the European list are American Samoa, Bahrain, Barbados, Grenada, Guam, South Korea, Macau, the Marshall Islands, Mongolia, Namibia, Palau, Panama, St Lucia, Samoa, Trinidad & Tobago, Tunisia and the UAE}}</ref><br />\n(\u0394) Identified on the first, and the largest, OECD 2000 list of 35 tax havens (the OECD list only contained Trinidad & Tobago by 2017); the above list contains 34 of the 35.<ref name=\"OECD havens\"/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book |last1      = Hines Jr.\n |first1     = James R.\n |last2      = Feldstein\n |first2     = Martin\n |title      = The Effects of Taxation on Multinational Corporations\n |publisher  = University of Chicago Press\n |isbn       = 978-0226240954\n |year       = 1995\n |url-access = registration\n |url        = https://archive.org/details/effectsoftaxatio0000unse\n}}\n\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Hines Jr.\n  | first = James R.\n  | title = International Taxation and Multinational Activity\n  | publisher = University of Chicago Press\n  | isbn = 978-0226341736\n  | year = 2001\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/internationaltax0000unse\n  }}\n\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Hines Jr.\n  | first = James R.\n  | title = International Taxation\n  | publisher =  Edward Elgar\n  | isbn =    978-1843764465\n  | year = 2007\n   }}\n\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Hines Jr.\n  | first = James R.\n  | title = Taxing Corporate Income in the 21st Century\n  | publisher =  Cambridge University Press\n  | isbn =    978-1107411517\n  | year = 2012\n   }}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Economy|Companies}}\n*[[Dhammika Dharmapala]]\n*[[Conduit and Sink OFCs]]\n*[[Gabriel Zucman]]\n*[[Ireland as a tax haven]]\n*[[United States as a tax haven]]\n*[[Double Irish|Double Irish, Single Malt, and CAIA]], BEPS tools\n*[[Joel Slemrod]]\n\n==Sources==\n===Academic research{{anchor|Most important papers on tax havens}}===\nThe following are the most cited papers on tax havens as ranked on the IDEAS/RePEc economic papers database,<ref name=\"respec\"/> of the [[Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis]], over the last 25 years.\n\nAs well as being the most cited individual author on tax havens, Hines has authored or co-authored five of the ten most referenced papers on tax havens.<ref name=\"respec\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: