ofbeethoveni01schi Vol. 1]  [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbeethoveni02schi Vol. 2] NB This is a translation into English of Schindler's ''Biographie von Ludwig van Beethoven'' (1840), with supplemental material supplied by Moscheles to the publisher.\n*{{cite book\n |ref=harv   <!--  {{sfn|Schnabel|1993|p=167}} -->\n |last=Schnabel\n |first=Wolfgang\n |title=Die evangelische Posaunenchorarbeit. Herkunft und Auftrag\n |language=German\n |publisher=Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht\n |year=1993\n |url=https://books.google.de/books?id=7b0u8N6YLXIC&lpg=PA167}}\n*{{cite book\n |ref=harv   <!-- {{sfn|Seyfried|1827|p=}} -->\n |last=Seyfried\n |first=Ignaz von\n |author-link=Ignaz von Seyfried\n |title=Trauser-Gesang / bey / Beethoven's Leichenbeg\u00e4ngnisse / in Wien den 29. M\u00e4rz 1827. / Vierstimmiger M\u00e4nnerchor, / mit willk\u00fchrlicher Begleitung / von vier Posaunen, oder des Pianoforte\n |place=Vienna\n |publisher=[[Tobias Haslinger]]\n |language=German\n |year=1827<!-- Also June 1827?, see https://web.archive.org/web/20160913103914/http://www.lvbeethoven.it/Articoli/1827/Beethoven-Articoli-1827.html -->\n |url=https://www.beethoven-haus-bonn.de/sixcms/detail.php//dokseite_digitales_archiv_en/_dokid/bb:T00023867/_seite/1}}\n*{{cite book\n |ref=harv   <!-- {{sfn|Spitzer|2017|p=228}} -->\n |last=Spitzer\n |first=Michael\n |title=Beethoven\n |publisher=Routledge\n |year=2017\n |isbn=9781351574297\n |url=https://books.google.de/books?id=xCgxDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT228}}\n* {{cite book\n |ref=harv   <!-- {{sfn|Suppan|2006|}} -->\n |last=Suppan\n |first=Wolfgang\n |title=Stadtpfeifer\n |work=[[Oesterreichisches Musiklexikon]]\n |series=Volume 5, Online edition\n |language=German\n |isbn=3700130775\n |publisher=Verlag der \u00d6sterreichischen Akademie der Wissenschaften\n |place=Vienna\n |year=2006 \n |url=http://www.musiklexikon.ac.at/ml/musik_S/Stadtpfeifer.xml}}\n*{{cite book\n |ref=harv   <!-- {{sfn|Voss|2012|p=3}} -->\n |last=Voss\n |first=Egon\n |title=Drei Equale f\u00fcr vier Posaune\n |chapter=Foreword\n |series=(Beethoven Werke, Abteilung VI, Band 1: Kammermusik mit Blasinstrumenten)\n |language=English, German, French\n |publisher=Henle Verlag\n |place=Munich\n |year=2012\n |url=http://www.henle.de/media/foreword/1151.pdf}}\n{{col div end}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://imslp.org/wiki/3_Equali,_WoO_30_(Beethoven,_Ludwig_van) IMSLP] Scores.\n* Performance by trombonists of the [http://techtv.mit.edu/videos/15342-beethoven-three-equale-for-four-trombones-woo-30 MIT Symphony Orch (MITSO), cond. Neal Stulberg] on YouTube\n\n[[Category:Compositions by Ludwig van Beethoven]]\n[[Category:Compositions for trombone]]\n[[Category:Funerary and memorial compositions]]\n[[Category:1812 compositions]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSources:Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three_Equals_for_four_trombones,_WoO_30"}
{"title_page": "Kapalua Airport", "text_new": "{{Infobox airport\n| name         = Kapalua Airport\n| nativename   = ''Kahua Mokulele o Kapalua''\n| image        = Kapalua Airport Terminal 2009.jpg\n| image-width  = 250\n| caption      = Airport terminal, 2009\n| IATA         = JHM\n| ICAO         = PHJH\n| FAA          = JHM\n| type         = Private use, publicly owned\n| owner        = [[Hawaii Department of Transportation]]\n| operator     = \n| city-served  = [[Lahaina, Hawaii]]\n| location     = [[Kapalua, Hawaii]]\n| elevation-f  = 256\n| website      = [http://hawaii.gov/jhm Hawaii.gov/JHM]\n| coordinates  = {{coord|20|57|47|N|156|40|23|W|region:US-HI_scale:10000|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map            = United States Maui#USA Hawaii\n| pushpin_mapsize        = 250\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location of airport on Maui##Location of airport in Hawaii\n| pushpin_label          = '''JHM'''\n| pushpin_label_position = bottom\n| r1-number    = 2/20\n| r1-length-f  = 3,000\n| r1-surface   = Asphalt\n| stat-year    = 2004\n| stat1-header = Aircraft operations\n| stat1-data   = 9,990\n| footnotes    = Source: [[Federal Aviation Administration]]<ref name=\"FAA\">{{FAA-airport|ID=JHM|use=PR|own=PU|site=52390.*A}}. Federal Aviation Administration. Effective April 5, 2012.</ref>\n}}\n[[File:Starr-110412-5113-Digitaria insularis-habit view Kapalua Airport-Kahana West Maui-Maui (24989436711).jpg|thumb|Kapalua Airport, April 2011]]\n'''Kapalua Airport''' {{Airport codes|JHM|PHJH|JHM}}, also known as '''Kapalua\u2013West Maui Airport''', is a regional private use [[airport]] on the west side of the island of [[Maui]] in [[Hawaii]]. It is located five&nbsp;[[nautical mile]]s (6&nbsp;[[mile|mi]], 9&nbsp;[[kilometre|km]]) north of [[Lahaina, Hawaii|Lahaina]], in [[Maui County]].<ref name=\"FAA\" /> Most flights to Kapalua Airport originate from commuter airports on the other Hawaiian islands by commercial commuter services, unscheduled air taxis, and general aviation.\n\nAs per [[Federal Aviation Administration]] records, the airport had 52,328 passenger boardings (enplanements) in [[calendar year]] 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/passenger_allcargo_stats/passenger/media/cy08_all_enplanements.pdf|title=Enplanements for CY 2008|last=|first=|date=December 18, 2009|work=|publisher=Federal Aviation Administration|format=PDF, 1.0 MB|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}\n</ref> 42,416 enplanements in 2009, and 40,060 in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/passenger_allcargo_stats/passenger/media/cy10_all_enplanements.pdf|title=Enplanements for CY 2010|last=|first=|date=October 4, 2011|work=|publisher=Federal Aviation Administration|format=PDF, 189 KB|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}\n</ref> It is included in the [[Federal Aviation Administration]] (FAA) [[National Plan of Integrated Airport Systems]] for 2017\u20132021, in which it is [[FAA airport categories|categorized]] as a [[general aviation]] facility.<ref name=\"NPIAS Airports\">{{cite web|title=List of NPIAS Airports|url=https://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/npias/reports/media/NPIAS-Report-2017-2021-Appendix-A.pdf|website=FAA.gov|publisher=Federal Aviation Administration|accessdate=23 December 2016|format=PDF|date=21 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nNamed for the [[Kapalua Resort]] a few miles to the north, the airport replaced the [[Kaanapali Airport]], which had an even shorter runway, in 1987 to allow valuable coastal land to be developed.<ref>{{cite news |title= Pilots return to dedicate Kaanapali Airport monument  |newspaper= Lahaina News |author= Mark Vieth |date= July 1, 2010 |url= http://www.lahainanews.com/page/content.detail/id/501040/Pilots-return-to-dedicate-Kaanapali-Airport-monument.html |accessdate= November 10, 2010 }}</ref> The airport code name JHM stands for John Henry Magoon, who was president of [[Hawaiian Airlines]] when that airline developed the airport. Hawaiian operated [[de Havilland Canada DHC-7 Dash 7]] turboprop aircraft on flights to [[Honolulu]]. The [[STOL]] capable, four engine, 50-passenger Dash 7 was the largest aircraft ever to operate scheduled passenger flights from the airport. Hawaiian discontinued service to Kapalua when the Dash 7 was retired from its fleet in 1994.\n\n[[Mahalo Air]], which operated between 1993 and 1997, also served Kapalua with flights to Honolulu using [[ATR 42]] twin turboprop aircraft.\n\nIsland Air discontinued service to Kapalua on May 31, 2013 when it replaced its fleet of Dash-8 with ATR-72 aircraft.\n\nOn November 2, 2016, Hawaiian Airlines announced they would resume service at Kapalua Airport beginning January 18, 2017 with flights to Honolulu and [[Kahului]]. Flights were to be operated by Hawaiian Air's [[Hawaiian Airlines#.CA.BBOhana by Hawaiian|{{Okina}}Ohana by Hawaiian]] subsidiary utilizing 48-seat [[ATR 42#ATR 42.E2.80.93500|ATR 42-500]] twin turboprop aircraft.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2016/11/03/business/business-breaking/hawaiian-airlines-starts-selling-kapalua-tickets/\n|date=2016-11-03\n|accessdate=2016-11-07\n|title=Hawaiian Airlines starts selling Kapalua tickets\n|publisher=Honolulu Star-Advertiser\n}}\n</ref>\n\nOn November 15, 2016, Hawaiian Airlines announced that it was temporarily suspending sales of its Honolulu to West Maui service pending securing a TSA presence at Kapalua Airport.\n\nOn January 11, 2017, Hawaiian Airlines announced they expect to resume service at Kapalua West Maui Airport by late March.\n\nOn January 27, 2017, Hawaiian Airlines resumed selling tickets to and from Kapalua West Maui Airport, with service beginning March 1, 2017.\n\nOn March 25, 2020, Hawaiian Airlines suspended service to and from Kapalua West Maui Airport as part of its system \nwide reduction in service due to the Covid-19 pandemic.\n\n== Facilities and aircraft ==\nKapalua Airport is governed by a special agreement made by the state with Maui County.  A former, privately owned airport, major changes or improvements to Kapalua Airport cannot be made without the consent of the Maui County Council.  The county insists on limiting development to preserve the Kapalua community from commercialization.  Kapalua Airport is restricted to a single runway, a couple of terminal facilities and support facilities.  There are no air cargo facilities.  Operations are restricted to daytime hours only. Passengers departing on 'Ohana Airlines will pass through TSA screening. Passengers departing on Mokulele Airlines are not screened by TSA.\n\nThe United States Department Of Agriculture maintains an inspection station from 7:30 am to 1:45 pm. Passengers whose final destination is the U.S. mainland must have their checked bags inspected and tagged if they are checking their bags through to their final U.S. mainland destination. Passengers departing Kapalua Airport on flights departing after 1:45 pm will be unable to check their bags through to U.S. mainland destinations and will have to collect their checked bags at baggage claim in Honolulu, have them inspected by Honolulu U.S.D.A., check in at their Honolulu Airport airline's ticket counter, and pass through TSA security in Honolulu to continue on to their final U.S. mainland destination. Agricultural inspection is only required for bags departing Hawaii bound for the U.S. mainland.\n\nThere is a snack bar offering a variety of light snacks, meals, and beverages.\n\nThe airport covers an area of 50 [[acre]]s (20 [[hectare|ha]]) at an [[elevation]] of 256 feet (78 m) above [[mean sea level]]. It has one [[runway]] designated 2/20 with an [[asphalt]] surface measuring 3,000 by 100 feet (914 x 30 m). For the 12-month period ending December 31, 2004, the airport had 9,990 aircraft operations, an average of 27 per day: 51% [[airline|scheduled commercial]] and 49% [[air taxi]].<ref name=\"FAA\" />\n\n== Airlines and destinations ==\nThe following [[airline]]s offer scheduled passenger service:\n{{Airport destination list \n| [[Hawaiian Airlines]] | [[Honolulu International Airport|Honolulu]]\n| [[Mokulele Airlines]] |  [[Honolulu International Airport|Honolulu]], [[Kona International Airport|Kailua\u2013Kona]], [[Molokai Airport|Molokai]]\n}}\n\nMakani Kai Air, Big Island Air, and Royal Pacific Air provide unscheduled, on-demand charter flights and tours.\n\n== Authority ==\nKapalua Airport is part of a centralized state structure governing all of the airports and seaports of Hawaii.  The official authority of Kapalua Airport is the [[Governor of Hawaii]] who appoints the Director of the [[Hawaii Department of Transportation]] who has jurisdiction over the Hawaii Airports Administrator.\n\nThe Hawaii Airports Administrator oversees six governing bodies: Airports Operations Office, Airports Planning Office, Engineering Branch, Information Technology Office, Staff Services Office, Visitor Information Program Office.  Collectively, the six bodies have authority over the four airport districts in Hawaii: [[Hawaii (island)|Hawai{{okina}}i Island District]], [[Kauai|Kaua{{okina}}i District]], Maui District and the principal [[Honolulu County, Hawaii|O{{okina}}ahu District]].  Kapalua Airport is a subordinate of the Maui District officials.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://hawaii.gov/jhm Hawaii DOT page for Kapalua Airport]\n* {{US-airport2|JHM|PHJH}}\n\n{{Portalbar|Hawaii|United States|Aviation|Transport}}\n{{Airports in Hawaii}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Maui County, Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Airports in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Maui County, Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 1987]]\n[[Category:1987 establishments in Hawaii]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox airport\n| name         = Kapalua Airport\n| nativename   = ''Kahua Mokulele o Kapalua''\n| image        = Kapalua Airport Terminal 2009.jpg\n| image-width  = 250\n| caption      = Airport terminal, 2009\n| IATA         = JHM\n| ICAO         = PHJH\n| FAA          = JHM\n| type         = Private use, publicly owned\n| owner        = [[Hawaii Department of Transportation]]\n| operator     = \n| city-served  = [[Lahaina, Hawaii]]\n| location     = [[Kapalua, Hawaii]]\n| elevation-f  = 256\n| website      = [http://hawaii.gov/jhm Hawaii.gov/JHM]\n| coordinates  = {{coord|20|57|47|N|156|40|23|W|region:US-HI_scale:10000|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map            = United States Maui#USA Hawaii\n| pushpin_mapsize        = 250\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location of airport on Maui##Location of airport in Hawaii\n| pushpin_label          = '''JHM'''\n| pushpin_label_position = bottom\n| r1-number    = 2/20\n| r1-length-f  = 3,000\n| r1-surface   = Asphalt\n| stat-year    = 2004\n| stat1-header = Aircraft operations\n| stat1-data   = 9,990\n| footnotes    = Source: [[Federal Aviation Administration]]<ref name=\"FAA\">{{FAA-airport|ID=JHM|use=PR|own=PU|site=52390.*A}}. Federal Aviation Administration. Effective April 5, 2012.</ref>\n}}\n[[File:Starr-110412-5113-Digitaria insularis-habit view Kapalua Airport-Kahana West Maui-Maui (24989436711).jpg|thumb|Kapalua Airport, April 2011]]\n'''Kapalua Airport''' {{Airport codes|JHM|PHJH|JHM}}, also known as '''Kapalua\u2013West Maui Airport''', is a regional private use [[airport]] on the west side of the island of [[Maui]] in [[Hawaii]]. It is located five&nbsp;[[nautical mile]]s (6&nbsp;[[mile|mi]], 9&nbsp;[[kilometre|km]]) north of [[Lahaina, Hawaii|Lahaina]], in [[Maui County]].<ref name=\"FAA\" /> Most flights to Kapalua Airport originate from commuter airports on the other Hawaiian islands by commercial commuter services, unscheduled air taxis, and general aviation.\n\nAs per [[Federal Aviation Administration]] records, the airport had 52,328 passenger boardings (enplanements) in [[calendar year]] 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/passenger_allcargo_stats/passenger/media/cy08_all_enplanements.pdf|title=Enplanements for CY 2008|last=|first=|date=December 18, 2009|work=|publisher=Federal Aviation Administration|format=PDF, 1.0 MB|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}\n</ref> 42,416 enplanements in 2009, and 40,060 in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/passenger_allcargo_stats/passenger/media/cy10_all_enplanements.pdf|title=Enplanements for CY 2010|last=|first=|date=October 4, 2011|work=|publisher=Federal Aviation Administration|format=PDF, 189 KB|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}\n</ref> It is included in the [[Federal Aviation Administration]] (FAA) [[National Plan of Integrated Airport Systems]] for 2017\u20132021, in which it is [[FAA airport categories|categorized]] as a [[general aviation]] facility.<ref name=\"NPIAS Airports\">{{cite web|title=List of NPIAS Airports|url=https://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/npias/reports/media/NPIAS-Report-2017-2021-Appendix-A.pdf|website=FAA.gov|publisher=Federal Aviation Administration|accessdate=23 December 2016|format=PDF|date=21 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nNamed for the [[Kapalua Resort]] a few miles to the north, the airport replaced the [[Kaanapali Airport]], which had an even shorter runway, in 1987 to allow valuable coastal land to be developed.<ref>{{cite news |title= Pilots return to dedicate Kaanapali Airport monument  |newspaper= Lahaina News |author= Mark Vieth |date= July 1, 2010 |url= http://www.lahainanews.com/page/content.detail/id/501040/Pilots-return-to-dedicate-Kaanapali-Airport-monument.html |accessdate= November 10, 2010 }}</ref> The airport code name JHM stands for John Henry Magoon, who was president of [[Hawaiian Airlines]] when that airline developed the airport. Hawaiian operated [[de Havilland Canada DHC-7 Dash 7]] turboprop aircraft on flights to [[Honolulu]]. The [[STOL]] capable, four engine, 50-passenger Dash 7 was the largest aircraft ever to operate scheduled passenger flights from the airport. Hawaiian discontinued service to Kapalua when the Dash 7 was retired from its fleet in 1994.\n\n[[Mahalo Air]], which operated between 1993 and 1997, also served Kapalua with flights to Honolulu using [[ATR 42]] twin turboprop aircraft.\n\nIsland Air discontinued service to Kapalua on May 31, 2013 when it replaced its fleet of Dash-8 with ATR-72 aircraft.\n\nOn November 2, 2016, Hawaiian Airlines announced they would resume service at Kapalua Airport beginning January 18, 2017 with flights to Honolulu and [[Kahului]]. Flights were to be operated by Hawaiian Air's [[Hawaiian Airlines#.CA.BBOhana by Hawaiian|{{Okina}}Ohana by Hawaiian]] subsidiary utilizing 48-seat [[ATR 42#ATR 42.E2.80.93500|ATR 42-500]] twin turboprop aircraft.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2016/11/03/business/business-breaking/hawaiian-airlines-starts-selling-kapalua-tickets/\n|date=2016-11-03\n|accessdate=2016-11-07\n|title=Hawaiian Airlines starts selling Kapalua tickets\n|publisher=Honolulu Star-Advertiser\n}}\n</ref>\n\nOn November 15, 2016, Hawaiian Airlines announced that it was temporarily suspending sales of its Honolulu to West Maui service pending securing a TSA presence at Kapalua Airport.\n\nOn January 11, 2017, Hawaiian Airlines announced they expect to resume service at Kapalua West Maui Airport by late March.\n\nOn January 27, 2017, Hawaiian Airlines resumed selling tickets to and from Kapalua West Maui Airport, with service beginning March 1, 2017.\n\nOn March 25, 2020, Hawaiian Airlines suspended service to and from Kapalua West Maui Airport as part of it's system \nwide reduction in service due to the Covid-19 pandemic.\n\n== Facilities and aircraft ==\nKapalua Airport is governed by a special agreement made by the state with Maui County.  A former, privately-owned airport, major changes or improvements to Kapalua Airport cannot be made without the consent of the Maui County Council.  The county insists on limiting development to preserve the Kapalua community from commercialization.  Kapalua Airport is restricted to a single runway, a couple of terminal facilities and support facilities.  There are no air cargo facilities.  Operations are restricted to daytime hours only. Passengers departing on 'Ohana Airlines will pass through TSA screening. Passengers departing on Mokulele Airlines are not screened by TSA.\n\nThe United States Department Of Agriculture maintains an inspection station from 7:30 am to 1:45 pm. Passengers whose final destination is the U.S. mainland must have their checked bags inspected and tagged if they are checking their bags through to their final U.S. mainland destination. Passengers departing Kapalua Airport on flights departing after 1:45 pm will be unable to check their bags through to U.S. mainland destinations and will have to collect their checked bags at baggage claim in Honolulu, have them inspected by Honolulu U.S.D.A., check in at their Honolulu Airport airline's ticket counter, and pass through TSA security in Honolulu to continue on to their final U.S. mainland destination. Agricultural inspection is only required for bags departing Hawaii bound for the U.S. mainland.\n\nThere is a snack bar offering a variety of light snacks, meals, and beverages.\n\nThe airport covers an area of 50 [[acre]]s (20 [[hectare|ha]]) at an [[elevation]] of 256 feet (78 m) above [[mean sea level]]. It has one [[runway]] designated 2/20 with an [[asphalt]] surface measuring 3,000 by 100 feet (914 x 30 m). For the 12-month period ending December 31, 2004, the airport had 9,990 aircraft operations, an average of 27 per day: 51% [[airline|scheduled commercial]] and 49% [[air taxi]].<ref name=\"FAA\" />\n\n== Airlines and destinations ==\nThe following [[airline]]s offer scheduled passenger service:\n{{Airport destination list \n| [[Hawaiian Airlines]] | [[Honolulu International Airport|Honolulu]]\n| [[Mokulele Airlines]] |  [[Honolulu International Airport|Honolulu]], [[Kona International Airport|Kailua\u2013Kona]], [[Molokai Airport|Molokai]]\n}}\n\nMakani Kai Air, Big Island Air, and Royal Pacific Air provide unscheduled, on-demand charter flights and tours.\n\n== Authority ==\nKapalua Airport is part of a centralized state structure governing all of the airports and seaports of Hawaii.  The official authority of Kapalua Airport is the [[Governor of Hawaii]] who appoints the Director of the [[Hawaii Department of Transportation]] who has jurisdiction over the Hawaii Airports Administrator.\n\nThe Hawaii Airports Administrator oversees six governing bodies: Airports Operations Office, Airports Planning Office, Engineering Branch, Information Technology Office, Staff Services Office, Visitor Information Program Office.  Collectively, the six bodies have authority over the four airport districts in Hawaii: [[Hawaii (island)|Hawai{{okina}}i Island District]], [[Kauai|Kaua{{okina}}i District]], Maui District and the principal [[Honolulu County, Hawaii|O{{okina}}ahu District]].  Kapalua Airport is a subordinate of the Maui District officials.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://hawaii.gov/jhm Hawaii DOT page for Kapalua Airport]\n* {{US-airport2|JHM|PHJH}}\n\n{{Portalbar|Hawaii|United States|Aviation|Transport}}\n{{Airports in Hawaii}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Maui County, Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Airports in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Maui County, Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 1987]]\n[[Category:1987 establishments in Hawaii]]\n", "name_user": "Neils51", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling - it's->its,typo(s) fixed: privately- \u2192 privately", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kapalua_Airport"}
